Perhaps its fate that today is the 4th of July and you will once again be fighting for our freedom, nor for tyranny oppression or persecution but from annihilation. We are fighting for our right to live. To exist and should we win the day, the fourth of July will no longer be known as an American holiday but as the day when the world declared in one voice we will not go quietly into the night. text: I just love how stupidly comical people will hang on to old cliches that have long since dried up, and never had that much relevance in the first place.  People always like to point out so-called "Obvious expendables" every time, when this has not been true for a number of films & programs.    Night of the Living Dead, guess who would have been the sole survivor had he not been mistaken for a zombie after the others had all died?   The sequel to that film, Dawn of the Dead killed half of the main characters and left the other half on an unresolved cliffhanger.  Guess who they were?  Friday the Thirteenth part ii had no less than THREE allegedly expendable characters who ultimately escaped Jason's wrath.   The original Independence Day had one air force man survive the massacre, and it wasn't Harry Connick JR.   What compels people to desperately cling to cliches that were never all that relevant in the first place, and even less so now?  Are they that determined to look stupid or nitpicky?  They will cherry pick films that reaffirm their silly claims, then conveniently ignore anything that contradicts them.    Jeepers Creepers.  Japanese films.  Quarantine. Record. The Twilight Zone. The Severed Arm. A Bucket of Blood. The Terminator. The War of the Worlds. The Texas Chainsaw Massacre. The Day After Tomorrow. Man on Fire.  Disaster on the Coastliner. Animated films with actors you would never know were X or Y if you didn't know them to begin with.  I could go on and on.

text: Wow. What an odd and peculiar road Independence Day has travelled to get to this‚Äì a sequel 20 years later. After it was initially released in 1996 it was recognized as a box office juggernaut but panned by critics and savvy audiences alike. Then it took on this identity as being a cheesy, "what were we thinking" type of picture for many years. But in more recent years it has been looked back upon with more fondness as being a movie so cheesy & ridiculous that it's now become a good movie. Perhaps it was just youthful nostalgia but audiences opinions of Independence Day has softened over the years and now look where it is‚Äì It's getting a sequel! Only in America...
